===Verb===
{{en-verb|speaks|speaking|spoke|past2=spake|past2_qual=archaic|spoken|past_ptc2=spoke|past_ptc2_qual=colloquial, nonstandard}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[communicate]] with one's [[voice]], to [[say]] [[word]]s [[out loud]].
#* {{RQ:Maxwell Mirror and the Lamp|chapter=XXV|page=203|passage=And Vickers launched forth into a tirade very different from his platform utterances. He '''spoke''' with extreme contempt of the dense stupidity exhibited on all occasions by the working classes. He said that if you wanted to do anything for them, you must rule them, not pamper them.}}
#: {{ux|en|I was so surprised I couldn't '''speak'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|You're '''speaking''' too fast.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|reciprocal}} To have a [[conversation]].
#: {{ux|en|It's been ages since we've '''spoken'''.}}
# {{lb|en|by extension}} To [[communicate]] or [[converse]] by some means other than [[orally]], such as [[writing]] or [[facial]] [[expressions]].
#: {{ux|en|He '''spoke''' of it in his diary.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Speak''' to me only with your eyes.}}
#: {{ux|en|Actions '''speak''' louder than words.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To deliver a message to a group; to deliver a [[speech]].
#: {{ux|en|This evening I shall '''speak''' on the topic of correct English usage.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To be able to communicate in a [[language]].
#: {{ux|en|He '''speaks''' Mandarin fluently.}}
## {{lb|en|by extension}} To be able to communicate in the manner of specialists in a field.
##* {{quote-book|en| title=Computer Analysis and Qualitative Research| page=4| url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0803974833| author=Nigel G Fielding, Raymond M Lee| year=1998| passage=Even those who did ''''speak''' computer' did so sometimes in a less than fluent way which required a jump to be made from a press-the-right-button stage to having the confidence to experiment.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[utter]].
#* {{RQ:King James Version|book=Jeremiah|chapter=9|verse=5|passage= And they will deceive every one his neighbour, and will not speak the truth: they have taught their tongue to '''speak''' lies, and weary themselves to commit iniquity.}}
#: {{ux|en|I was so surprised that I couldn't '''speak''' a word.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[communicate]] (some fact or feeling); to [[bespeak]], to [[indicate]].
#* '''1785''', {{w|Frances Burney}}, ''Diary and letters of Madame d'Arblay, author of Evelina, Cecilia, &c.'', [https://archive.org/details/diarylettersofma02burn2/page/392/mode/1up link]:
#*: Their behaviour to each other '''speaks''' the most cordial confidence and happiness.
#* {{RQ:Melville Moby-Dick|chapter=A Bosom Friend.|page=56|passage=There he sat, his very indifference '''speaking''' a nature in which there lurked no civilized hypocrisies and bland deceits.}}
# {{lb|en|informal|transitive|sometimes|humorous}} To [[understand]] (as though it were a language).
#: {{ux|en|Sorry, I don't '''speak''' idiot.}}
#: {{ux|en|So you can program in C. But do you '''speak''' C++?}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To produce a sound; to [[sound]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Macbeth|V|vi|page=150|passage=Make all our trumpets '''speak'''.}}
# Of a bird, to be able to vocally reproduce words or phrases from a human language.
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1936|author=Rollo Ahmed|title=The Black Art|publisher=Long|location=London|page=220|passage=Miles tremblingly confessed that it had, but to no purpose; a parrot being able to '''speak''' better in three weeks than a brazen head.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To [[address]]; to [[accost]]; to speak to.
#* {{RQ:KJV|Ecclesiasticus|13|6|passage=[He will] thee in hope; he will '''speak''' thee fair.}}
#* {{RQ:Emerson Threnody|page=239|passage=Each village senior paused to scan / And '''speak''' the lovely caravan.}}
#* '''2013''', George Francis Dow, ''Slave Ships and Slaving'' (quoting an older text)
#*: '''Spoke''' the ship ''Union'' of Newport, without any anchor. The next day ran down to Acra, where the windlass was again capsized and the pawls broken.

====Usage notes====
* Saying that one speaks a language often means that one ''can'' or ''knows how to'' speak it ("I speak Italian"); similarly, "I don't speak Italian" usually means that one cannot, rather than that one chooses not to.

